With rusqlite's parameterized queries, the entire payload is treated as a literal string value by the SQLite engine. The SQL parser never sees the injection characters as syntax.

Each variant carries exactly the data relevant to that event. Use unit variants for signals, tuple variants for single payloads, struct variants for multiple fields.

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub enum StreamEvent {
    /// Plain text -- carries the text content
    Text(String),
    /// Signal: tool call block detected (no data needed)
    ToolCallStart,
    /// Complete parsed tool call
    ToolCallComplete(ParsedToolCall),
    /// Partial tool call content for display during streaming
    ToolCallPartial(String),
}

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub enum ToolProgress {
    /// Completion percentage 0-100
    Percent(u8),
    /// Human-readable status message
    Status(String),
    /// Partial output streamed during execution
    PartialOutput(String),
}
```

Consumption pattern:
```rust
for event in parser.feed(chunk) {
    match event {
        StreamEvent::Text(text) => display_text(&text),
        StreamEvent::ToolCallStart => show_spinner(),
        StreamEvent::ToolCallComplete(call) => {
            let result = registry.execute(&call.name, call.args(), &ctx).await?;
            display_result(&result);
        }
        StreamEvent::ToolCallPartial(partial) => update_spinner(&partial),
    }
}
```

Design rules:
- `#[derive(Debug, Clone)]` on all event enums -- they get logged, buffered, and inspected
- Use `String` not `&str` -- events outlive the chunk that produced them
- Prefer tuple variants `Foo(T)` over struct variants `Foo { data: T }` for single payloads
- Document each variant with `///` -- these are your API surface

You need a stateful parser that buffers content and only emits events when boundaries are unambiguous. The key insight is the `safe_emit_len` function -- it checks if the end of your buffer could be the start of a tag you're looking for.

For example, if your buffer is `"hello <tool_"` and you're looking for `"<tool_call>"`, the suffix `"<tool_"` matches a prefix of the tag, so you can only safely emit `"hello "` (the first 6 bytes).

```rust
fn safe_emit_len(&self, tag: &str) -> usize {
    let buf = self.buffer.as_bytes();
    let tag_bytes = tag.as_bytes();
    for suffix_start in (1..=buf.len().min(tag_bytes.len())).rev() {
        let suffix = &buf[buf.len().saturating_sub(suffix_start)..];
        if tag_bytes.starts_with(suffix) {
            return buf.len() - suffix.len();
        }
    }
    buf.len()
}
```

This handles the worst case: single-character chunks where `<` arrives in one chunk, `t` in the next, `o` in the next, etc. Each time you call `feed()`, the buffer grows and you check if you have enough to make a decision.

Always implement a `flush()` method for stream termination:

```rust
pub fn flush(&mut self) -> Vec<StreamEvent> {
    let mut events = Vec::new();
    if self.inside_tool_call {
        self.tool_call_buffer.push_str(&self.buffer);
        if !self.tool_call_buffer.is_empty() {
            events.push(StreamEvent::ToolCallPartial(self.tool_call_buffer.clone()));
        }
    } else if !self.buffer.is_empty() {
        events.push(StreamEvent::Text(self.buffer.clone()));
    }
    self.buffer.clear();
    self.tool_call_buffer.clear();
    self.inside_tool_call = false;
    events
}
```

Two cases: (1) Stream ended mid-tool-call -- emit what we have as `ToolCallPartial` so the agent loop can handle the incomplete call gracefully. (2) Stream ended with buffered text -- emit it. Never silently discard buffered content on flush.

Create a bounded channel, pass the sender to the worker, and receive from the consumer side.

```rust
use tokio::sync::mpsc;

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub enum ToolProgress {
    Percent(u8),
    Status(String),
    PartialOutput(String),
}

pub struct ToolExecution {
    pub cancel: CancelToken,
    pub progress_rx: mpsc::Receiver<ToolProgress>,
}

// In the registry:
pub fn create_execution_context(&self) -> (CancelToken, mpsc::Receiver<ToolProgress>) {
    let cancel = CancelToken::new();
    let (_tx, rx) = mpsc::channel(64); // bounded buffer of 64 messages
    (cancel, rx)
}

// In the tool implementation:
async fn execute_with_cancel(
    &self, params: Value, ctx: &ToolContext,
    cancel: &CancelToken,
    progress: Option<mpsc::Sender<ToolProgress>>,
) -> Result<ToolResult> {
    if let Some(tx) = &progress {
        tx.send(ToolProgress::Status("Starting...".into())).await.ok();
    }
    // ... do work ...
    if let Some(tx) = &progress {
        tx.send(ToolProgress::Percent(50)).await.ok();
    }
    Ok(ToolResult::success("done"))
}
```

Key points:
- Use `mpsc::channel(64)` not unbounded -- backpressure prevents memory blowup
- `.await.ok()` on send -- ignores errors if receiver dropped (non-critical)
- `Option<mpsc::Sender>` -- progress reporting is optional, not all callers care
- The receiver is `!Clone` -- only one consumer, which is what you want for progress display

Use the `#[tokio::test]` attribute macro instead of `#[test]`. This sets up a tokio runtime for the test.

```rust
// Sync test -- no runtime needed
#[test]
fn test_cancel_token_starts_uncancelled() {
    let token = CancelToken::new();
    assert!(!token.is_cancelled());
}

// Async test -- needs tokio runtime
#[tokio::test]
async fn test_execute() {
    let mut reg = ToolRegistry::new();
    reg.register(DummyTool);
    let ctx = ToolContext {
        cwd: PathBuf::from("/tmp"),
        project_path: PathBuf::from("/tmp"),
    };
    let result = reg.execute("dummy", json!({}), &ctx).await.unwrap();
    assert!(!result.is_error);
    assert_eq!(result.output, "done");
}

// Async test with spawned tasks
#[tokio::test]
async fn test_concurrent_execution() {
    let reg = Arc::new(ToolRegistry::with_defaults());
    let mut handles = Vec::new();
    for _ in 0..5 {
        let reg = reg.clone();
        handles.push(tokio::spawn(async move {
            let ctx = ToolContext {
                cwd: PathBuf::from("/tmp"),
                project_path: PathBuf::from("/tmp"),
            };
            reg.execute("bash", json!({"command": "echo ok"}), &ctx).await
        }));
    }
    for h in handles {
        assert!(h.await.unwrap().is_ok());
    }
}
```

Guidelines:
- Use `#[test]` for sync code (pure functions, data structures)
- Use `#[tokio::test]` for anything that calls `.await`
- `#[tokio::test]` creates a single-threaded runtime by default. For multi-threaded tests: `#[tokio::test(flavor = "multi_thread")]`
- Keep test setup synchronous when possible -- only go async for the actual operation under test
- Use `TempDir::new().unwrap()` for filesystem tests -- auto-cleanup on drop

Review this code for security issues:
```rust
fn validate_model_name(name: &str) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    if name.is_empty() {
        anyhow::bail!("empty model name");
    }
    if !name.contains('/') {
        anyhow::bail!("model name must be owner/repo format");
    }
    if name.contains("..") {
        anyhow::bail!("path traversal in model name");
    }
    Ok(())
}
```

This validation has multiple gaps:

**1. Missing null byte check (P0).** Attack: `owner/repo\0../../etc/passwd`. The null byte truncates the string at the C layer (e.g., when passed to `CString::new` or filesystem APIs), so validation sees `owner/repo` but the OS sees a truncated path.

**2. Missing absolute path check (P0).** Attack: `/etc/passwd` passes because it contains `/`. The validation requires a slash but doesn't check position.

**3. Missing newline check (P1).** Attack: `owner/repo\nHost: evil.com` could cause HTTP header injection when constructing download URLs.

**4. No character allowlist (P1).** URL metacharacters like `?`, `#`, `&` pass validation and could alter the download URL.

Fixed version:

```rust
fn validate_model_name(name: &str) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    if name.is_empty() {
        anyhow::bail!("empty model name");
    }
    if !name.contains('/') {
        anyhow::bail!("model name must be owner/repo format");
    }
    if name.starts_with('/') || name.starts_with('\\') {
        anyhow::bail!("absolute path in model name");
    }
    if name.contains("..") {
        anyhow::bail!("path traversal in model name");
    }
    if name.contains('\0') {
        anyhow::bail!("null byte in model name");
    }
    if name.contains('\n') || name.contains('\r') {
        anyhow::bail!("newline in model name");
    }
    // Allowlist: only permit safe characters
    if !name.chars().all(|c| c.is_alphanumeric() || "-_./".contains(c)) {
        anyhow::bail!("model name contains disallowed characters");
    }
    Ok(())
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_null_byte_blocked() {
    assert!(validate_model_name("owner/repo\0malicious").is_err());
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_absolute_path_blocked() {
    assert!(validate_model_name("/etc/passwd").is_err());
}

#[test]
fn test_p1_newline_blocked() {
    assert!(validate_model_name("owner/repo\nHost: evil.com").is_err());
}

#[test]
fn test_valid_name_passes() {
    assert!(validate_model_name("TheBloke/Llama-2-7B-GGUF").is_ok());
}
```

Defense in depth: even with URL encoding by the HTTP client, rejecting bad input early prevents entire classes of attacks.

Parameter overwrite is a P0 injection attack. The scenario: the model outputs a `file_write` tool call with `path=/tmp/safe.txt` followed by a second `path=/etc/passwd` parameter. If the parser uses a HashMap that overwrites on duplicate keys, the attacker's second value wins and the file gets written to `/etc/passwd`.

```xml
<tool_call>
<function=file_write>
<parameter=path>/tmp/safe.txt</parameter>
<parameter=content>ok</parameter><parameter=path>/etc/passwd</parameter>
</function>
</tool_call>
```

Fix: keep the first occurrence of each parameter.

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;
use regex::Regex;

pub fn parse_parameters(block: &str) -> HashMap<String, serde_json::Value> {
    let re = Regex::new(r"<parameter=(\w+)>(.*?)</parameter>").unwrap();
    let mut params = HashMap::new();

    for cap in re.captures_iter(block) {
        let key = cap[1].to_string();
        let value = serde_json::Value::String(cap[2].to_string());
        // SECURITY: entry().or_insert() keeps FIRST occurrence only
        params.entry(key).or_insert(value);
    }

    params
}

#[test]
fn test_p0_duplicate_parameter_keeps_first() {
    let block = "<parameter=path>/tmp/safe.txt</parameter>\n\
                  <parameter=content>ok</parameter>\
                  <parameter=path>/etc/passwd</parameter>";
    let params = parse_parameters(block);

    assert_eq!(
        params.get("path").unwrap().as_str().unwrap(),
        "/tmp/safe.txt",
        "CRITICAL: Must keep first path value, not attacker's second value"
    );
    assert_ne!(
        params.get("path").unwrap().as_str().unwrap(),
        "/etc/passwd",
        "Parameter overwrite attack must be blocked"
    );
}

#[test]
fn test_legitimate_different_params() {
    let block = "<parameter=path>/src/main.rs</parameter>\n\
                  <parameter=content>fn main() {}</parameter>";
    let params = parse_parameters(block);
    assert_eq!(params.len(), 2);
    assert_eq!(params["path"].as_str().unwrap(), "/src/main.rs");
    assert_eq!(params["content"].as_str().unwrap(), "fn main() {}");
}
```

The `HashMap::entry().or_insert()` pattern is the key: it only inserts if the key doesn't already exist. This is a one-line fix that prevents an entire class of parameter injection attacks.

Anthropic requires the system prompt as a top-level field, not as a message in the array:

```rust
fn convert_to_anthropic(&self, request: &ChatRequest) -> (Option<String>, Vec<serde_json::Value>) {
    let mut system = None;
    let mut messages = Vec::new();

    for msg in &request.messages {
        match msg.role {
            Role::System => {
                system = Some(msg.content.clone());  // Extract, don't include in messages
            }
            Role::User => {
                messages.push(json!({"role": "user", "content": msg.content}));
            }
            // ... other roles
        }
    }
    (system, messages)
}
```

Then in the request body:
```rust
let mut body = json!({
    "model": self.model,
    "max_tokens": request.max_tokens.unwrap_or(self.max_tokens),
    "messages": messages,
});
if let Some(sys) = &system {
    body["system"] = serde_json::Value::String(sys.clone());
}
```

For OpenAI, the system message stays in the messages array as `{"role": "system", "content": "..."}`. This is why the internal `ChatRequest` uses a flat `Vec<Message>` with role tags -- it's the simplest common denominator that both protocols can be derived from.

